Word based tokenisers drawback — OOV (Out Of Vocabulary) problem
Solved via. - Character based tokenisation —> but the word and the sentence looses meaning and context

Solution — Sub Word based tokenisation

 					—————

Imp : Byte- Pair Tokenizer —
	
	—> sub word based tokenisation
	—> Two rules : 1. Do NOT split frequent words into smaller subwords (they are important)
				  2. Split rare words … down to the char level
				  3. Introduced In 1994
				  4. Data compression algorithm
				  5. Most common pair of consecutive bytes of data is replaced with a byte that does NOT occur in data
			          6.  Can comprehend and encode unknown words as well by breaking them down into smaller subwords


	—> ILLUSTRATION :
- [ ] Consider data : aaabdaaabac
- [ ] The byte pair ‘aa’ occurs frequently
- [ ] Replace ‘aa’ with an external char, such a Z
- [ ] Compressed data. - ZabZabac
- [ ] The byte pair ‘ab’ occurs frequently
- [ ] Replace ‘ab’ with an external char, such a Y
- [ ] New Compressed data - ZYZYac

—> Example: suppose in a sentence data , ‘es’ occurs 13 times - a frequent byte pair - and after doing further char level encoding on this pair, we find out that ‘e’ occurs 16 times and hence ‘e’ alone occurs (16-13) times in the snetence and ’s’ occurs (13 -13) 0 times alone. 
—> This analysis is possible only because we did byte pair encoding first
